item.title: WHY Your Resume Is NOT Getting Shortlisted?! | Vishakha Sadhwani
item.description:
In this short, I‚Äôll share the exact resume format you need to get shortlisted in the top tech companies effortlessly in 2026.
Your resume doesn‚Äôt need to be complicated. It just needs the right structure.
Start with Education. Keep it simple: degree, university, year, GPA. Add coursework only if you‚Äôre applying for entry-level roles.
Then add Technical Skills. Put your strongest tools and platforms up front. The right keywords matter here because ATS actually uses them.
For Professional Experience, write clear points with an action verb, what you did, and why it mattered. Add metrics only where they make sense. Embedded links are great for showing proof of work.
If you‚Äôre early in your journey, Academic Projects become important. Use action verbs, mention the tools you used, and highlight the impact. No need to force numbers.
End with Relevant Projects or Volunteering. Hackathons, open source, and community work show how you collaborate and grow outside your job.

item.description:
To continue the research, do check this sheet: https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1eBpT8G_FHzstbYc7cDZZG_BsJgqCOGrFciLckEZq4A4/edit?usp=sharing
Prof. K. Nageshwar Rao‚ÄìSenior journalist, political analyst, and former MLC In this Telugu podcast episode, Prof. K. Nageshwar shares his decades-long journey through journalism, politics, media ethics, and democracy in India, offering rare clarity in an age of noise. From being part of India‚Äôs first 24-hour news ecosystem to witnessing the transformation of Telugu media, he reflects on how television debates, political drama, and narrative-driven journalism have reshaped public thinking.
Drawing from his experiences at institutions like The Indian Express, the early days of TV9, and his time as a legislator, he explains how money, power, and politics intersect, and why voters today are often ill-informed or misinformed rather than unaware. The conversation explores Parliamentary culture, student politics, university ecosystems like Osmania University, and why money alone cannot build great institutions without intellectual leadership.
He offers sharp insights into media, politics, business nexus, the delegitimisation of independent journalists, and why healthy opposition and free media are essential warning systems in a democracy. From caste reservation debates and manifesto politics to welfare schemes like Dalit Bandhu, he breaks down how policies are designed, sold, and judged, and what voters should truly evaluate.1
The episode also touches on threats faced by journalists and politicians, public perception, ideological labelling, AI in journalism, currency performance, and the responsibility of intellectual honesty. With references ranging from ancient Indian philosophy to contemporary global politics, this is a grounded, no-theatrics conversation on how democracy actually functions behind the scenes.
If you‚Äôre interested in Telugu politics, Indian democracy, journalism ethics, media influence, voter awareness, and political analysis without shouting, this episode offers perspective, depth, and calm reasoning. This helps you see it all clearly.

Top 3 Skills That Get You Hired
OS-level Networking Basics ‚Äì Understand the OSI model, IP, TCP, DNS, routing, and switching.
Firewall & Security Tools ‚Äì Work with firewalls, NAT, VPNs, and load balancers to secure and manage network traffic.
Cloud-native Networking ‚Äì Learn VPCs, Transit Gateway, PrivateLink, and hybrid connectivity in cloud platforms. Infrastructure as Code ‚Äì Use tools like Terraform to automate and manage cloud networks.

Yes, it‚Äôs funny. Yes, it‚Äôs a roast. But here‚Äôs the thing: behind all the jokes, there‚Äôs a real question.
If we can lose our minds for an international superstar, why do our own football players still struggle for basic respect and attention?
Laugh, enjoy, get roasted ‚Äî and think about it too. Watch till the end.
Ai Prompt: A high-resolution candid selfie taken at night inside a modern airport corridor. Bright white ceiling lights and glass walls run along the left side. In the front, using the uploaded photo as reference, a young man with a soft, charming smile holds the camera. He‚Äôs wearing a black blazer over a black shirt.
Just behind him, Lionel Messi is walking forward and looking at the camera with a relaxed, friendly smile. He‚Äôs dressed in a navy blue suit with a white crew-neck t-shirt. Around them are several airport security officers in dark uniforms, including one officer on the left wearing a peaked cap.
Everyone is captured mid-walk, giving a natural sense of motion with slight blur. The style is candid and documentary, with realistic colors, an eye-level view, shallow depth of field, and sharp focus on the young man and Messi in 4K quality.

In this video, I unbox the ECOVACS DEEBOT N20 Pro and share my first impressions + initial cleaning test: vacuum performance, vibrating mopping (OZMO Pro), mapping, app control, noise, and real-world usage on Indian floors (dust, hair, corners, carpets).
In this video, I compare Ecovacs Deebot N20 Pro vs Deebot N30 vs Deebot N30 Plus ‚Äî which one gives the best value for Indian homes (dust, hair, tiles, corners, carpets).
‚úÖ Key highlights (as per listed specs):‚Ä¢ 8000Pa suction power for deep cleaning ‚Ä¢ OZMO Pro vibrating mopping system (better than drag-only mops) ‚Ä¢ ZeroTangle / anti-hair tangle tech for pet/human hair ‚Ä¢ 5200mAh battery + claimed up to ~300 mins runtime / large home coverage üí∞ Current price reference (may change): around ‚Çπ28,999 on major platforms (India).
Unboxing Contents: The box includes the robot (white color), charging dock, side brush, anti-tangle main brush, washable mopping pads, a "dummy" tank (for vacuum-only mode), and a vibrating mopping module (OZMO Pro 2.0). Key Features & Upgrades (vs. Y1 Pro): * Suction Power: Upgraded to 8000 Pa (compared to lower suction on older models). * Runtime: Up to 300 minutes on a single charge. * Mopping: Features a vibrating mopping system (OZMO Pro 2.0) for better stain removal, unlike the static mop on the Y1 Pro. * Tangle-Free: Uses ZeroTangle‚Ñ¢ Technology (mentioned as "anti-tangle" in the video) with flat bristles and comb teeth to prevent hair buildup. Maintenance Tips (from Ecovacs Rep): * Dust Bin: 400ml capacity; the filter should be dry-cleaned (tapped or brushed), not washed with water. * Sensors: Clean the anti-drop and bumper sensors weekly with a dry cloth or earbud. * Tanks: Use the "dummy tank" when only vacuuming to maintain weight balance. Use the water tank only for mopping and fill with plain water (no chemical cleaners). * Brushes: The side and main brushes are detachable for easy cleaning of any trapped hair.

item.title: I NEVER Thought This Would Happen To Me! | Vishakha Sadhwani
item.description:
Vishakha Sadhwani: I NEVER Thought This Would Happen To Me! | Vishakha Sadhwani
I was the quiet, underconfident middle child who never imagined she‚Äôd end up in big tech, let alone in a different country.
And if you saw where I am today, you might think I always had everything figured out. But the truth is‚Ä¶ my entire career started because of one unexpected moment.
I missed my DU application deadline. A form didn‚Äôt reach on time, and the path I had planned for years disappeared overnight.
What felt like a massive failure back then quietly pushed me toward engineering‚Ä¶ and then toward opportunities I never would‚Äôve considered if life had gone ‚Äúaccording to plan.‚Äù
By my third year, I realised I wanted more than the predictable path everyone around me was taking. So I prepared on my own, took my exams, and moved to the U.S. for my Master‚Äôs.
That one decision changed everything.
It led me to three job offers after graduation, to AWS, to Google New York, to global conferences, to recognition from major publications, to the EB1A visa, and eventually to NVIDIA in California. It also helped me build a community of thousands of people who support me every day.
And all of this came from a moment I once thought was the end of my plans.
Sometimes the door that closes‚Ä¶ is the one that makes space for something bigger.
